Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

Exercise 1.2. Ask and use the database to analyze 5 questions about San Francisco. For each question, write at least 150 words and support your answer with plots. Make a map for at least 2 of the 5 questions.

You should try to come up with some questions on your own, but these are examples of reasonable questions:

  • Which parts of the city are the most and least expensive?
  • Which parts of the city are the most dangerous (and at what times)?
  • Are noise complaints and mobile food vendors related?
  • What are the best times and places to find food trucks?
  • Is there a relationship between housing prices and any of the other tables?

Please make sure to clearly state each of your questions in your submission.

For this question, we plotted locations of mobile food vendors and locations of noise complaints on 2 maps of San Fransisco. As we can see from the maps above, food vendor locations and noise complaints do seem to come from the same are, which is the north east part of San Francisco. As there are more noise complaints than there are food truck locations, the food truck points are less dense overall, However, there is a clear concentration on the eastern side of the city, and it gets even more concentrated on the north-east side of the city. There are many reasons why this may be the case. Food trucks are more likely to setup in areas with high concentrations of people. Areas with high concentrations of people are also more likely to receive noise complaints due to the number of people that complain/ number of people to complain about.

For this question I tackled it in two parts, where and when. I refer back to question 1.2.1 and the map of San Francisco with mobile food vendors charted. The highest concentration of food trucks are gathered on the north east side of the city with good distribution all along the eastern side of the city. For the best time to find food trucks, first I counted the food trucks open on a given day of the week from the mobile_food_schedule database. From this I could see that the weekdays had far more foodtrucks open than the weekends, probably due to food vendors wanting to serve working people on their lunch breaks. We can see this play out when we look at histograms of start and end hours of the food trucks. Many open before lunch at 8-11 am and service lunch break hours, and many close at 2-4 when lunch breaks end. There is also a large number of food trucks that open before 9 and close from 9-10. These food truck presumably open for the breakfast crowd. Therefore, if you want to eat at a food truck for lunch, consider going to the north-east side of the city at 11-2, or from 8-10 to eat breakfast.

I split this question into 2 similar to the way I did the previous problem, when and where. For where, I plotted a density plot over a map a San Francisco. I found that the highest concentration of crime happenes in the north-east side of the city. This further supports my hypothesis that the north-east side of the city is the most populated part of the city, therefore would be more crime in that area. For when crime happened, I plotted the number of occurence on days of the week, months, days of the month, and date. I found that crime happens evenly over the week, with slight upticks on Monday and Saturday. The most criminally active month is January. Crime tends to be higher on the first day of the month, then stays constant for the remainder of the month. Overall crime has stayed relatively constant since information was first tracked in 2010.

For this problem, we compare the maps of crime and schools. For the School Map, we plotted the schools in the city and color coded them based on if they are private or public. Private schools are colored in red while public schools are colored in yellow. Looking at the distribution of schools, it seems that schools are evenly distributed with only a slightly higher concentration in the north-eastern side of the city. Furthermore, comparing public schools and private schools, private schools are slightly more concentrated in the northeast side of the city, indicating that there may be more people in the northeastern part of the city and/or they may be more affluent than the rest of the city (due to the fact private schools can choose to locate where they generate the most profit, either with the most students our the highest tuition prices, while public schools are uniformly distributed, presumeably by the government.

  1. What is the relationship between housing price and Robberies?
In [24]:
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(10,10))
q = Basemap(resolution='f',
            projection='merc',
            lat_0=54.5, lon_0=-4.36,
            llcrnrlon=-122.539444, llcrnrlat=37.701479 , urcrnrlon=-122.345123, urcrnrlat=37.814395)
q.readshapefile('cb_2015_us_zcta510_500k','zip')
q.drawmapboundary(fill_color='#46bcec')
q.fillcontinents(color='#f2f2f2',lake_color='#46bcec',zorder=0)
q.drawcoastlines()
zillow = pandas.read_sql_query('SELECT RegionName,AVG(MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes) FROM zillow GROUP BY RegionName',con)
zillow.RegionName = zillow.RegionName.astype(str)
df_poly = pandas.DataFrame({
        'shapes': [Polygon(np.array(shape), True) for shape in q.zip],
        'RegionName': [area['GEOID10'] for area in q.zip_info]
    })
df_poly = df_poly.merge(zillow, on='RegionName',how = 'outer')
df_poly = df_poly.dropna()
cmap = plt.get_cmap('Oranges')   
pc = PatchCollection(df_poly.shapes, zorder=2)
norm = Normalize()

pc.set_facecolor(cmap(norm((df_poly['AVG(MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes)'].fillna(0).values))))
ax.add_collection(pc)
mapper = matplotlib.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=cmap)
mapper.set_array(df_poly['AVG(MedianSoldPricePerSqft_AllHomes)'].dropna())
plt.colorbar(mapper, shrink=0.4)
robs = crime[crime['Category'] == 'ROBBERY']
a,b = q(list(robs['Lon']),list(robs['Lat']))
q.plot(a,b,'b+',alpha = .01)
plt.show()

For this question, I plotted housing prices and colored in the zip code areas based on average median house price per square foot, where darker colors are more expensive areas. On top of this I plotted a subset of crimes (Robberies) and plotted them with high transparancy, so that it was easy to distinguish between high density of crime areas and low density of crime areas. As you can see from the map, housing prices are highest on the north-eastern side of the city, and robberies are also most frequent in the north-eastern side of the city. This makes sense as robbers will choose target expensive homes instead of wasting their time on poorer homes in order to maximize their risk vs reward. We can conclude based on this map that crime and housing price are positively correlated, and that expensive areas have higher incedence of robberies than poorer areas.
